<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-22T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-22T02:00:00-05:00" n="314" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d314">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/365: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-22T15:00:00+08:00">February 22, 1934—3
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 22—6:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>97. Your 43, February 17, 3 p.m.<note n="8" xml:id="d314fn8">Not
                                printed.</note></p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>In well-informed circles, North China, it is not believed that the
                                rise in price of silver has been an important factor in the increase
                                in trade.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>It is believed that depreciation of United States dollar has been
                                a very important factor.</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>Other factors have been (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) increasing
                                confidence among businessmen in the United States, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) purchases by American importers of Chinese
                                products in anticipation of further rise in price of silver.</item>
                            <label>4.</label>
                            <item>There is a belief among North China foreign bankers that a
                                stabilization of the price of silver would be a great benefit all
                                around but they fear that if price is stabilized too high there
                                would result a sharp contraction in trade and the Chinese Government
                                might be inspired to depreciate Chinese silver dollars.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>